# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bootstrap-css
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] As of May 2023, Bootstrap is the 17th most starred project (4th most starred library) on GitHub, with over 164,000 stars.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] According to W3Techs, Bootstrap is used by 19.2% of all websites.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] Bootstrap is an HTML, CSS and JS library that focuses on simplifying the development of informative web pages (as opposed to web applications).
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] The primary purpose of adding it to a web project is to apply Bootstrap's choices of color, size, font and layout to that project.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] As such, the primary factor is whether the developers in charge find those choices to their liking.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] Once added to a project, Bootstrap provides basic style definitions for all HTML elements.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] The result is a uniform appearance for prose, tables and form elements across web browsers.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] In addition, developers can take advantage of CSS classes defined in Bootstrap to further customize the appearance of their contents.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] For example, Bootstrap has provisioned for light- and dark-colored tables, page headings, more prominent pull quotes, and text with a highlight.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] Bootstrap also comes with several JavaScript components which do not require other libraries like jQuery.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] They provide additional user interface elements such as dialog boxes, tooltips, progress bars, navigation drop-downs, and carousels.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] Each Bootstrap component consists of an HTML structure, CSS declarations, and in some cases accompanying JavaScript code.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] They also extend the functionality of some existing interface elements, including for example an auto-complete function for input fields.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] The most prominent components of Bootstrap are its layout components, as they affect an entire web page.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] The basic layout component is called "Container", as every other element in the page is placed in it.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] Developers can choose between a fixed-width container and a fluid-width container.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] Once a container is in place, other Bootstrap layout components implement a CSS Flexbox layout through defining rows and columns.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] A precompiled version of Bootstrap is available in the form of one CSS file and three JavaScript files that can be readily added to any project.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] The raw form of Bootstrap, however, enables developers to implement further customization and size optimizations.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] This raw form is modular, meaning that the developer can remove unneeded components, apply a theme and modify the uncompiled Sass files.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] Bootstrap, originally named Twitter Blueprint, was developed by Mark Otto and Jacob Thornton at Twitter in 2010 as a framework to encourage consistency across internal tools.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] Before Bootstrap, various libraries were used for interface development, which led to inconsistencies and a high maintenance burden.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] After a few months of development by a small group, many developers at Twitter began to contribute to the project as a part of Hack Week, a hackathon-style week for the Twitter development team.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] It was renamed from Twitter Blueprint to Twitter Bootstrap and released as an open-source project on August 19, 2011.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] It has continued to be maintained by Otto, Thornton, a small group of core developers, and a large community of contributors.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] On January 31, 2012, Bootstrap 2 was released, which added built-in support for Glyphicons, several new components, as well as changes to many of the existing components.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] This version supports responsive web design, meaning the layout of web pages adjusts dynamically, taking into account the characteristics of the device used (whether desktop, tablet, mobile phone).
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] Shortly before the release of Bootstrap 2.1.2, Otto and Thornton left Twitter, but committed to continue to work on Bootstrap as an independent project.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] On August 19, 2013, Bootstrap 3 was released.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] It redesigned components to use flat design and a mobile first approach.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] Bootstrap 3 features new plugin system with namespaced events.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] Bootstrap 3 dropped Internet Explorer 7 and Firefox 3.6 support, but there is an optional polyfill for these browsers.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] Bootstrap 3 was also the first version released under the twbs organization on GitHub instead of the Twitter one.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] Otto announced Bootstrap 4 on October 29, 2014.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] The first alpha version of Bootstrap 4 was released on August 19, 2015.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] The first beta version was released on August 10, 2017.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] Otto suspended work on Bootstrap 3 on September 6, 2016, to free up time to work on Bootstrap 4.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] Bootstrap 4 was finalized on January 18, 2018.
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] Bootstrap 4 supports the latest versions of Google Chrome, Firefox, Internet Explorer, Opera, and Safari (except on Windows).
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] It additionally supports back to IE10 and the latest Firefox Extended Support Release (ESR).
[src:bootstrap-css/bootstrap-front-end-framework] Bootstrap 5 was officially released on May 5, 2021.
[src:bootstrap-css/css-flexible-box-layout] The **CSS flexible box layout** module defines a CSS box model optimized for user interface design, and the layout of items in one dimension.
[src:bootstrap-css/css-flexible-box-layout] In the flex layout model, the children of a flex container can be laid out in any direction, and can "flex" their sizes, either growing to fill unused space or shrinking to avoid overflowing the parent.
[src:bootstrap-css/css-flexible-box-layout] Both horizontal and vertical alignment of the children can be easily manipulated.
[src:bootstrap-css/css-flexible-box-layout] In the following example, a container has been set to `display: flex`, which means that the three child items become flex items.
[src:bootstrap-css/css-flexible-box-layout] The value of `justify-content` has been set to `space-between` in order to space the items out evenly on the main axis.
[src:bootstrap-css/css-flexible-box-layout] An equal amount of space is placed between each item with the left and right items being flush with the edges of the flex container.
[src:bootstrap-css/css-flexible-box-layout] You can also see that the items are stretching on the cross axis, due to the default value of `align-items` being `stretch`.
[src:bootstrap-css/css-flexible-box-layout] The items stretch to the height of the flex container, making them each appear as tall as the tallest item.
