[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Before responsive web design became the standard approach for making websites work across different device types, web developers used to talk about mobile web design, mobile web development, or sometimes, mobile-friendly design.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] These are basically the same as responsive web design — the goals are to make sure that websites work well across devices with different physical attributes (screen size, resolution) in terms of layout, content (text and media), and performance.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] HTML is fundamentally responsive, or *fluid*.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] If you create a web page containing only HTML, with no CSS, and resize the window, the browser will automatically reflow the text to fit the viewport.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] While the default responsive behavior may sound like no solution is needed, long lines of text displayed full screen on a wide monitor can be difficult to read.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] This problem can be solved with CSS, for example by creating narrow columns to limit the line length.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] However, this can create new problems for users that narrow their browser window or view the site on a mobile device — the columns will look squashed and become harder to read.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Creating a non-resizable web page by setting a fixed width doesn't work either; that leads to scroll bars on narrow devices and too much empty space on wide screens.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Responsive web design, or RWD, is a design approach that addresses the full range of available devices and device sizes, enabling automatic adaption to the screen, whether the content is viewed on a tablet, phone, television, or watch.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Responsive web design isn't a separate technology — it is an approach.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] It is a term used to describe a set of best practices used to create a layout that can *respond* to any device being used to view the content.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] The term *responsive design*, coined by Ethan Marcotte in 2010, described using fluid grids, fluid images, and media queries to create responsive content.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] At the time, the recommendation was to use CSS `float` for layout and media queries to query the browser width, creating layouts for different breakpoints.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Fluid images are set to not exceed the width of their container; they have their `max-width` property set to `100%`.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Fluid images scale down when their containing column narrows but do not grow larger than their intrinsic size when the column grows.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] This enables an image to scale down to fit its content, rather than overflow it, but not grow larger and become pixelated if the container becomes wider than the image.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Modern CSS layout methods are inherently responsive, and, since the publication of Marcotte's article, we have a multitude of features built into the web platform to make designing responsive sites easier.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] The rest of this article will explain the various web platform features you might want to use when creating a responsive site.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Media queries allow us to run a series of tests (for example, whether the user's screen is greater than a certain width or resolution) and apply CSS selectively to style the page appropriately for the user's needs.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] For example, the following media query tests to see if the current web page is being displayed as screen media (therefore not a printed document) and the viewport is at least `80rem` wide.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] The `.container` rule will only be applied if these two things are true.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] You can add multiple media queries within a stylesheet, tweaking your whole layout or parts of it to best suit the various screen sizes.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] The points at which a media query is introduced, and the layout changes, are known as *breakpoints*.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] A common approach when using media queries is to create a simple single-column layout for narrow-screen devices (for example, mobile phones), then check for wider screens and implement a multiple-column layout when you know that you have enough screen width to handle it.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Designing for mobile first is known as **mobile first** design.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] If using breakpoints, best practices encourage defining media query breakpoints with relative units rather than absolute sizes of an individual device.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] There are different approaches to the styles defined within a media query block; ranging from using media queries to `<link>` style sheets based on browser size ranges to only including custom properties variables to store values associated with each breakpoint.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Media queries can help with RWD, but are not a requirement.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Flexible grids, relative units, and minimum and maximum unit values can be used without media queries.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Responsive sites are built on flexible grids, meaning you don't need to target every possible device size with pixel perfect layouts.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] By using a flexible grid, you can change a feature or add in a breakpoint and change the design at the point where the content starts to look bad.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] For example, to ensure line lengths don't become unreadably long as the screen size increases you can use `columns`; if a box becomes squashed with two words on each line as it narrows you can set a breakpoint.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Several layout methods — including Flexbox, and CSS Grid — are responsive by default.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] They all assume that you are trying to create a flexible grid and give you easier ways to do so.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] In flexbox, flex items shrink or grow, distributing space between the items according to the space in their container.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] By changing the values for `flex-grow` and `flex-shrink` you can indicate how you want the items to behave when they encounter more or less space around them.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] In the example below the flex items will each take an equal amount of space in the flex container, using the shorthand of `flex: 1` as previously discussed (see Flexbox: Flexible sizing of flex items).
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Here's how we could use flexbox with a media query for responsive design.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] The layout will change between a single-column and a two-column layout when the size of the above example crosses the `600px` width threshold.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] In CSS grid layout the `fr` unit allows the distribution of available space across grid tracks.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] The next example creates a grid container with three tracks sized at `1fr`.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] This will create three column tracks, each taking one part of the available space in the container.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] You already looked at this approach (see Flexible grids with the fr unit for a recap).
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Here's how we could use grid layout with a media query for responsive design.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Again, try resizing your browser window — you should see the example layout change at the `600px` width threshold, in the same way as the previous example.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] This scales media elements to ensure they never overflow their containers.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Responsive typography describes changing font sizes within media queries or using viewport units to reflect lesser or greater amounts of screen real estate.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] In this example, we want to set our level 1 heading to be `4rem`, meaning it will be four times our base font size.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] We only want this jumbo heading on larger screen sizes, therefore we first give the heading a smaller size of `2rem`, then use media queries to overwrite it with the larger size if we know that the user has a screen width of at least `1200px`.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] The next example is a modified version of our earlier responsive grid example, which includes a responsive heading using the method outlined.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] As with previous examples, try changing the browser window width, and note how not only the layout changes at the `600px` width threshold, but also the heading size.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] As this approach to typography shows, you do not need to restrict media queries to only changing the layout of the page.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] They can be used to tweak any element to make it more usable or attractive at alternate screen sizes.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Viewport units `vw` can also be used to enable responsive typography, without the need for setting breakpoints with media queries.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] `1vw` is equal to one percent of the viewport width, meaning that if you set your font size using `vw`, it will always relate to the size of the viewport.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] The problem with doing the above is that the user loses the ability to zoom any text set using the `vw` unit, as that text is always related to the size of the viewport.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] **Therefore you should never set text using viewport units alone**.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] There is a solution, and it involves using `calc()`.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] If you add the `vw` unit to a value set using a fixed size such as `em`s or `rem`s then the text will still be zoomable.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] This means that we only need to specify the font size for the heading once, rather than set it up for mobile and redefine it in the media queries.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] The font then gradually increases as you increase the size of the viewport.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Try resizing the browser window, as before, and note how this time the heading size increases *gradually* as the width changes.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] If you look at the HTML source of a responsive page, you will usually see the following `<meta>` tag in the `<head>` of the document.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] This `viewport` meta tag tells mobile browsers that they should set the width of the viewport to the device's width, and scale the document to 100% of its intended size, which shows the document at the mobile-optimized size that you intended.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Because mobile browsers tend to lie about their viewport width.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] This meta tag exists because when smartphones first arrived, most sites were not mobile optimized.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] The mobile browser would, therefore, set the viewport width to 980 pixels, render the page at that width, and show the result as a zoomed-out version of the desktop layout.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Users could zoom in and pan around the website to view the bits they were interested in, but it looked bad.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] By setting `width=device-width` you are overriding a mobile device's default, like the iPhone's default `width=980px`, with the actual width of the device.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Without it, your responsive design with breakpoints and media queries may not work as intended on mobile browsers.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] If you've got a narrow screen layout that kicks in at 480px viewport width or less, but the device is saying it is 980px wide, that user will not see your narrow screen layout.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] There are a number of other options you can put inside the `content` attribute of the viewport meta tag — see the `<meta name="viewport">` reference for more details.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Responsive design refers to a site or application design that responds to the environment in which it is viewed.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] It encompasses a number of CSS and HTML features and techniques and is essentially how we build websites by default.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Consider the sites that you visit on your phone — it is probably fairly unusual to come across a site that is the desktop version scaled down, or where you need to scroll sideways to find things.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] This is because the web has moved to this approach of designing responsively.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] It has also become much easier to achieve responsive designs with the help of the layout methods covered in this article.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] If you are new to web development today you have many more tools at your disposal than in the early days of responsive design.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] It is therefore worth checking the age of any materials you are using.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] While the historical articles are still useful, modern use of CSS and HTML makes it far easier to create elegant and useful designs, no matter what device your visitor views the site with.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-design] Next, we will study media queries in more detail and show how to use them to solve some common problems.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] , on a computer screen (left) and on a mobile phone screen (right).
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] The elements rearrange themselves into a more mobile friendly layout.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] Responsive web design became more important as users of mobile devices came to account for the majority of website visitors.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] In 2015, for instance, Google announced Mobilegeddon and started to boost the page ranking of mobile-friendly sites when searching from a mobile device.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] Responsive web design is an example of user interface plasticity.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] Luke Wroblewski has summarized some of the responsive and mobile design challenges and created a catalog of multi-device layout patterns.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] He suggested that, compared with a simple responsive web design approach, device experience or RESS (responsive web design with server-side components) approaches can provide a user experience that is better optimized for mobile devices.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] Server-side CSS generator implementation of stylesheet languages like Sass can be part of such an approach.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] Google has recommended responsive design for smartphone websites over other approaches.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] Although many publishers have implemented responsive designs, one challenge for responsive design adoption was that some banner advertisements and videos were not fluid.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] However, search advertising and (banner) display advertising came to support specific device platform targeting and different advertisement size formats for desktop, smartphone, and basic mobile devices.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] Different landing page URLs have been used for different platforms, or Ajax has been used to display different advertisement variants on a page.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] CSS tables permitted hybrid fixed and fluid layouts.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] There have been many ways of validating and testing responsive web designs, ranging from mobile site validators and mobile emulators to simultaneous testing tools like Adobe Edge Inspect.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] The Chrome, Firefox and Safari browsers and developer tools have offered responsive design viewport resizing tools, as do third parties.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] The W3C specification of HTML+ stated that websites have to be rendered according to the user preferences.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] The customization of web page layout was lacking however.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] Many web developers resorted to ordinary HTML tables as a way to customize the layout and bring some basic responsiveness to their websites at the same time.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] Limited browser capabilities meant that for Internet Explorer, the layout could adapt dynamically in the browser whereas, for Netscape, the page had to be reloaded from the server when resized.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] Cameron Adams created a demonstration in 2004.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] By 2008, a number of related terms such as "flexible", "liquid", "fluid", and "elastic" were being used to describe layouts.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] CSS3 media queries were almost ready for prime time in late 2008/early 2009.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] Ethan Marcotte coined the term *responsive web design*—and defined it to mean fluid grid / flexible images / media queries—in a May 2010 article in *A List Apart*.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] He described the theory and practice of responsive web design in his brief 2011 book titled *Responsive Web Design*.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] Responsive design was listed as #2 in Top Web Design Trends for 2012 by .net magazine after progressive enhancement at #1.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] Mashable called 2013 the Year of Responsive Web Design.
[src:bootstrap-css/responsive-web-design] User interface plasticity is the capacity of a user interface to withstand variations of both the system's physical characteristics and the environment while preserving usability.
